<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>What happens to the cyclical component of the budget deficit during a recession?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Cyclical deficit decreases</option>
            <option letter="b">Cyclical deficit increases</option>
            <option letter="c">Cyclical deficit stays constant</option>
            <option letter="d">Cyclical deficit becomes a surplus</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The cyclical component of the budget deficit increases during a recession because tax revenues automatically fall and transfer payments automatically rise as economic activity declines.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does an increase in expected future inflation affect current consumption?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Decreases current consumption</option>
            <option letter="b">Increases current consumption</option>
            <option letter="c">Has no effect on current consumption</option>
            <option letter="d">Only affects future consumption</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>An increase in expected future inflation tends to increase current consumption as people buy goods sooner to avoid higher prices in the future, particularly for durable goods.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What determines the steepness of the aggregate demand curve?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">The size of the wealth effect only</option>
            <option letter="b">The size of the interest rate effect only</option>
            <option letter="c">The combined size of wealth, interest rate, and foreign trade effects</option>
            <option letter="d">The unemployment rate</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>The steepness of the aggregate demand curve is determined by the combined magnitude of the wealth effect, interest rate effect, and foreign trade effect in response to price level changes.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does an increase in labor force participation affect the natural rate of unemployment?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Always decreases the natural rate</option>
            <option letter="b">Always increases the natural rate</option>
            <option letter="c">Initially may increase the natural rate</option>
            <option letter="d">Has no effect on the natural rate</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>An increase in labor force participation may initially increase the natural rate of unemployment as new workers enter the labor force and experience frictional unemployment while searching for jobs.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
